			<abstract>
				<p>Testimony of 18-year-old S .W. depicting ghettoization in Aknaszlatina/Slatina (Subcarpathia), deportation to and selection in
					Auschwitz, his suffering in the Buna-Monowitz labor camp and the youth block of the Buchenwald concentration camp, and his
					liberation in Theresienstadt.</p>
			</abstract>
		</profileDesc>
	</teiHeader>
	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1178_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: If I had to and were able to
				present all the misery I experienced I could talk for weeks but I do not do it gladly as remembering is horrible. Already in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/693176/solotvyno.html">Aknaszlatina</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1124" type="subject">Hungarians</term> treated us in a horrible way.
				They terribly tortured us, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">grabbed all our
					valuables</term> but that was not all. They said we kept treasures even under our skin, and they treated us accordingly. They
				searched us undressed, unfortunately not only us but also our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819"
					type="subject">wives</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject"
				>daughters</term>. Even high-ranking officers watched this performance. When we learnt they were going to take us away we were glad to
				go. Anywhere, just away from there. Leaving behind <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/693176/solotvyno.html"
					>Aknaszlatina</placeName> we travelled 90 of us in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522"
					type="subject">freight car</term> and arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2"
					>Birkenau</placeName> three days later. On the way many of us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745"
					type="subject">died</term> in the freight car because we got no water. In <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName> we had to get off the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> and leave our entire luggage behind.
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">Women</term> were led to the right, three of us
				brothers and my father to the left. Having walked a little, unfortunately, also our father was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">separated</term> from us. The day after, we were moved
				to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName>, where we stayed for three days. We got tattoos
				here and went on to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Buna</placeName>, 8 kilometres from
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName>. <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1178_02.jpg"/> We had to lay cables in the ground. We had to carry heavy cables in a distance of 4 kilometres;
				my back aches even today if I think of it. Nevertheless, our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496"
					type="subject">camp</term> was clean and we also got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					type="subject">food</term>. They harmed only those who could not <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>, but they would beat these <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> ruthlessly. When the front got closer
				they transferred us into <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43">Buchenwald</placeName>. We travelled
				130 of us in a little open freight car in the freezing cold of <date when="1945-01">January</date>. We received 500 grams of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> for the journey. Many <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">perished</term> during this journey. 12,000 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> departed but I doubt there were as many
				as 6,000 of us when we arrived. When we got off the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject"
					>train</term> the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> immediately
				approached and shot the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> who could not
				walk but sat down. Naturally, we had to watch it without saying a word; otherwise they would have shot us as well, since they had the
				weapon. In <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43">Buchenwald</placeName> we got into quarantine. We
				did not <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> here at all as this was a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selecting</term> place. In the cold of <date
					when="1945-01">January</date>, in the freezing cold of the mornings we were being lined up for 2-6 hours during <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll calls</term>. We had to suffer unbearably. Many
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> during the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll calls</term>. They just threw these <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> out of line. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">Crematorium</term> was working day and night but could
				not cope with the great number of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">dead
				bodies</term>. Later, I was singled out from block 51 and got into the <q>youthful</q> block, no. 66. We did not <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> either here but at least we did not need
				to leave the block but lined up for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll
					calls</term> inside. It was somewhat better here. Our leader was a <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs"
					>Czech</term> who treated us so nicely that it is difficult to find the words to describe it. He treated us like a father his
				children. Although he was also a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoner</term>,
				with limited opportunities, he still managed to obtain even <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					type="subject">food</term> for us. The <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004291">English</orgName>
				were already quite close when we were also taken away after 8 weeks of stay. There were 60,000 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43">Buchenwald</placeName> of very diverse nationalities, out of whom
				10,000 of us were Jews. I cannot give dates, since we were not humans here, but lived like the most miserable beasts. In <date
					when="1945-04">April</date>, when, as I have said, <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004291"
					>English</orgName> troops got closer, we left <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43"
					>Buchenwald</placeName>. They hurriedly entrained us in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2812482/weimar.html"
					>Weima</placeName>r, putting 100 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>
				in a car. Travelling for 14 days back and forth, (since there was no place where they accepted us), we arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449">Theresienstadt</placeName>, where <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Russians</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us. My future plans? I do not know.
				First, I would like to find out whether there are surviving members of my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">family</term>, and will make plans only
				afterwards.</p>
